{{Infobox Senator |honorific-prefix = |name = Armistead Thomson Mason |honorific-suffix = |image = Armistead Thompson Mason.jpg |imagesize = 200px |jr/sr=United States Senator |state = [[Virginia]] |term_start = January 3, 1816 |term_end = March 4, 1817 |preceded = [[William Branch Giles]] |succeeded = [[John Wayles Eppes]] |succeeding = <!--the name of the incumbent senator--> | birth_date ={{Birth date|1787|8|4}} | birth_place =Armisteads, [[Louisa County, Virginia]] | death_date ={{Death date and age|1819|2|6|1787|8|4}} | death_place =[[Bladensburg, Maryland]] | nationality = | party = [[Democratic-Republican Party]] | spouse = Charlotte Eliza Taylor | relations = | children = Stevens Thomson Mason | residence = [[Selma (Leesburg, Virginia)|Selma]], [[Leesburg, Virginia|Leesburg]], Virginia | alma_mater =[[The College of William & Mary]] | occupation = [[lawyer]], planter | profession = | cabinet = | committees = | portfolio = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }} '''Armistead Thomson Mason''' (August 4, 1787{{spaced ndash}}February 6, 1819),<ref name=GH>{{cite web | url=http://www.gunstonhall.org/library/masonweb/p7.htm#i350 | title=Armistead Thomson Mason | date=| accessdate=2015-10-27 | publisher=Gunston Hall}}</ref><ref name=PG>{{cite web | url=http://politicalgraveyard.com/families/10855.html | title=Mason family of Virginia | date= June 16, 2008| accessdate=2009-03-07 | publisher=The Political Graveyard| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090321031659/http://politicalgraveyard.com/families/10855.html| archivedate= 21 March 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> the son of [[Stevens Thomson Mason (Virginia)|Stevens Thomson Mason]],<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> was a [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] from [[Virginia]] from 1816 to 1817. Mason was also the second-youngest person to ever serve in the US Senate at the age of 28 and 5 months even though the age of requirement for the US Senate in the constitution is 30 years old.
==Early life and education== He was born at Armisteads in [[Louisa County, Virginia]], graduated from the [[College of William and Mary]] in 1807 and engaged in agricultural pursuits until he became colonel of [[Virginia Volunteers]] in the [[War of 1812]] and subsequently brigadier general of [[Virginia Militia]].
==Political career== He was elected as a [[Democratic-Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] to the United States Senate to fill the vacancy caused by the resignation of [[William Branch Giles]], [[United States Senate#Qualifications|despite being constitutionally underage for the office]]. Mason served from January 3, 1816, to March 4, 1817. He then moved to [[Loudoun County, Virginia|Loudoun County]], Virginia where he was an unsuccessful candidate for election to the [[15th United States Congress|Fifteenth Congress]] ([[United States House of Representatives elections in Virginia, 1817|1817]]). It was a bitter campaign that gave rise to several duels: Mason himself was later killed in a duel with his second cousin, [[John Mason McCarty]], at [[Bladensburg Duelling Field]], [[Maryland]], as a result of this campaign. He is buried in the churchyard of the Episcopal Church at [[Leesburg, Virginia|Leesburg]], Virginia.<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/>
==Marriage and children== Mason married on 1 May 1817 to Charlotte Eliza Taylor (died 1846) at Dr. Charles Cocke's in [[Albemarle County, Virginia|Albemarle County]], Virginia.<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> The couple had one son:<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/>
*Stevens Thomson Mason (1819&ndash;14 June 1847)<ref name=GH/>
==Relations== Armistead Thomson Mason was the grandnephew of [[George Mason]] (1725&ndash;1792);<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> grandson of [[Thomson Mason]] (1733&ndash;1785);<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> son of Mary Elizabeth "Polly" Armistead Mason (1760&ndash;1825) and [[Stevens Thomson Mason (Virginia)|Stevens Thomson Mason]] (1760&ndash;1803);<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> nephew of [[John Thomson Mason]] (1765&ndash;1824);<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> second cousin of [[Thomson Francis Mason]] (1785&ndash;1838) and [[James Murray Mason]] (1798&ndash;1871);<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> brother-in-law of [[William T. Barry|William Taylor Barry]] (1784&ndash;1835); brother of [[John Thomson Mason (1787–1850)|John Thomson Mason]] (1787&ndash;1850);<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> uncle of [[Stevens T. Mason|Stevens Thomson Mason]] (1811&ndash;1843);<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/> and first cousin of [[John Thomson Mason, Jr.]] (1815&ndash;1873).<ref name=GH/><ref name=PG/>
