{{Infobox company | name = Del Pezzo Restaurant | logo = | type = | industry = [[Restaurant]] | fate = | predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = --> | successor = <!-- or: | successors = --> | founded = <!-- if known: {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], [[state]], [[country]] --> | founder = <!-- or: | founders = --> | defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | hq_location_city = [[New York City]] | hq_location_country = | area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = --> | key_people = | products = | owner = <!-- or: | owners = --> | num_employees = | num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) --> | parent = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }}
'''Del Pezzo Restaurant''' was an eatery located at 211 West [[34th Street (Manhattan)|34th Street]] (and later, on West [[40th Street (Manhattan)|40th]] and West [[47th Street (Manhattan)|47th]])<ref name="Durling">[[E.V. Durling]], [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=tmhQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CxAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6407%2C1995254 "Women Make Life Stretch"], ''[[Milwaukee Sentinel]]'', November 18, 1955.</ref> in [[New York City]]. It was frequented by singers connected with the [[Metropolitan Opera Company]] in the early 1930s.<ref>''Police Slay Thug Who Defied Search'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 20, 1931, pg. 5.</ref> It was a favorite restaurant of [[Enrico Caruso]];<ref name="Durling"/><ref>Simone Cinotto, ''The Italian American Table: Food, Family, and Community in New York City'' ([[University of Illinois Press]], 2013), {{ISBN|978-0252095016}}, p. 199. [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZXBiAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA199&dq=%22Del%20Pezzo's%22%20caruso&pg=PA199#v=onepage&q=%22Del%20Pezzo's%22%20&f=false Excerpts available] at [[Google Books]].</ref> he and [[Giacomo Puccini]] dined there during the latter's visit to the United States in December 1906. They were joined by Marziale Sisca, the dean of [[Italian-American]] publishers, who owned the newspaper ''La Follia''.<ref>''Puccini in America'', [[American Heritage (magazine)|American Heritage]], April 1959, Volume X Issue 3.</ref> The restaurant was also frequented by ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine staff members<ref>[[Charles Champlin]], ''A Life in Writing: The Story of an American Journalist'' ([[Syracuse University Press]], 2006), {{ISBN|978-0815608479}}, p. 129. [https://books.google.com/books?id=P8lL1KpopEwC&lpg=PA129&ots=WhyTqmm6ip&dq=%22del%20pezzo%22%20restaurant%20life&pg=PA129#v=onepage&q=%22del%20pezzo%22%20restaurant%20life&f=false Excerpts available] at [[Google Books]].</ref> and by artists, such as the group that first met in 1950 to establish [[Raphael Soyer]]'s ''Reality'' magazine.<ref>Andrew Hemingway, ''Artists on the Left: American Artists and the Communist Movement, 1926-1956'' ([[Yale University Press]], 2002), {{ISBN|978-0300092202}}, p. 239. [https://books.google.com/books?id=Sl0M-Gev_uQC&lpg=PA239&dq=%22Del%20Pezzo%22%20Restaurant&pg=PA238#v=onepage&q=%22Del%20Pezzo%22%20Restaurant&f=false Excerpts available] at [[Google Books]].</ref> It was also the restaurant where [[Le Corbusier]] had lunch during his stay in New York for working the preliminary studies of the [[Headquarters of the United Nations|United Nations Headquarters]], which were being prepared in a drafting room on the twenty-seventh floor of the RKO building.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hellman|first=Geoffrey H.|date=May 3, 1947|title=Profiles: From within and without II|url=|journal=The New Yorker|volume=|pages=36-53|via=}}</ref>
