'''Kila Haoda''' (born 21 September 1949) is a Papua New Guinean politician. He was the Governor of [[Central Province (Papua New Guinea)|Central Province]] from 2012 to 2017.<ref name="bio">{{cite web | url=http://www.parliament.gov.pg/member-of-parliament/bio/view/governor-central | title=Hon. Kila Haoda, MP | publisher=National Parliament of Papua New Guinea | accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pngec.gov.pg/docs/default-source/default-document-library/nominations.pdf?sfvrsn=0 | title=Nominations By Electorate | publisher=PNG Electoral Commission | accessdate=15 June 2017 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6rEbk3093 |archive-date=15 June 2017}}</ref>

Haoda was the human resources manager for New Britain Palm Oil Limited and operated a supermarket and liquor store in [[Kimbe]] before returning to his home province to build the successful [[March Girls Resort]] at [[Gaire]]. He was an unsuccessful candidate for [[Kairuku-Hiri District]] at the [[Papua New Guinean general election, 2007|2007 election]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Central people urged start | work=PNG Post Courier | date=30 July 2009 }}</ref> He contested the Central Provincial seat at the [[Papua New Guinean general election, 2012|2012 election]] and ousted Governor [[Alphonse Moroi]]; initially elected as an independent, he immediately joined the governing [[People's National Congress (Papua New Guinea)|People's National Congress]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Wenge faces defeat | work=PNG Post-Courier | date=27 July 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Elections nearing close | work=PNG Post-Courier | date=26 July 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=PNC (22 Declared) | work=PNG Post Courier | date=27 July 2012 }}</ref>

Haoda serves on the Appointments Permanent Committee and the Justice Referral Committee in the National Parliament, and also serves as chairman of the Central City Development Project Steering Committee.<ref name=bio /><ref>{{cite news | title=Central City project endorsed | work=PNG Post Courier | date=2 April 2013 }}</ref> In August 2012, he questioned the benefits of the [[PNG Gas]] project for his province, expressing concern about insufficient infrastructure gains. He initially supported [[Powes Parkop]]'s proposed "[[betel nut|buai]] ban" in September 2013, but had come out strongly against it by February 2014.<ref>{{cite news | title=Central, Gulf governors support Parkop's proposed buai ban | work=PNG Post-Courier | date=1 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Consider MP views on betelnut ban | work=PNG Post-Courier | date=17 February 2014 }}</ref> He complained of "undisciplined officers" that "continue to tarnish the name of our discipline force" after an incident where he claimed police enforcing the ban had "terrorised and humiliated" women and children.<ref>{{cite news | title=Police involvement in NCD betelnut ban questioned | work=PNG Post-Courier | date=19 February 2014 }}</ref>

Haoda initiated an education scheme in Central Province to assist students with school fees.<ref>{{cite news | title=Goilala misses out on scheme | work=PNG Post Courier | date=2 June 2014 }}</ref> In September 2014, he signed a memorandum of agreement to build a new satellite city on 300 hectares of farmland outside [[Port Moresby]] in conjunction with private developers.<ref>{{cite news | title=Satellite city for Central Province | work=PNG Post Courier | date=12 September 2014 }}</ref> In the same month, he unveiled a new five-year development plan for the province, reported to be the first of its kind in Central Province.<ref>{{cite news | title=Province launches development plan | work=PNG Post-Courier | date=15 September 2014 }}</ref> In 2014, he became the inaugural patron of the Central Province Premier Rugby Football League competition, which began to compete for the Kila Haoda Cup.<ref>{{cite news | title=Kila Haoda Cup to be bigger and better | work=PNG Post Courier | date=3 June 2015 }}</ref> In October 2014, he announced his opposition to the [[Trans-Island Highway]] project to connect Port Moresby with the rest of Papua New Guinea, citing the potential for social problems and conflict over land.<ref>{{cite news | title=Central Governor opposes Trans Island Highway | work=PNG Post-Courier | date=10 October 2014 }}</ref> In December 2014, he signed a memorandum of understanding with [[Eda Ranu]] for the Port Moresby water corporation to supply water to a number of villages in Central Province.<ref>{{cite news | title=Central, Eda Ranu sign water deal | work=PNG Post-Courier | date=5 December 2014 }}</ref>

In July 2015, Haoda initiated a provincial microfinance scheme in conjunction with [[MiBank]], in order to support small and medium enterprises and "to stop the free handout mentality".<ref>{{cite news | title=Central Province signs deal Increase SME sector | work=PNG Post-Courier | date=8 July 2015 }}</ref> He also pledged to implement an "e-government" system in an ongoing partnership with the [[Malaysia]]n government.<ref>{{cite news | title=Central plans for transition | work=PNG Post-Courier | date=4 November 2015 }}</ref> In December 2015, he announced his opposition to a proposal for a new military base at Gabadi over land issues.<ref>{{cite news | title=MPs upset over site for army base | work=PNG Post-Courier | date=23 December 2015 }}</ref> He is recontesting his seat for the People's National Congress at the [[Papua New Guinean general election, 2017|2017 election]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.looppng.com/elections/kila-haoda-nominates-57664 | title=Kila Haoda nominates | work=Loop PNG | date=27 April 2017 | accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>

He was defeated by [[Robert Agarobe]] at the [[Papua New Guinean general election, 2017|2017 election]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://pasifik.news/9882-2/ | title=Goal of removing O’Neill galvanises new PNG alliance | work=Pasifik | date=31 July 2017 | accessdate=5 August 2017}}</ref>

