{{nihongo|'''Takemune Kimura'''|木村 雄宗|Kimura Takemune|extra=February 10, 1931–February 14, 2006}} was a [[Japan]]ese businessman and former [[president]] of [[Mitsubishi Motors]]. Prior to his promotion in June 1995 he spent 37 years at the company's Mizushima manufacturing facility in [[Kurashiki, Okayama]], before becoming president of the Pajero Manufacturing Co. subsidiary in [[Sakahogi, Gifu]].<ref name="ap-djs">[https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/MoneyInvesting/edit/w-mitsub.html "Mitsubishi Motors Names New President, To Take Charge for Troubled U.S. Unit"], AP-Dow Jones News Services, April 26, 1996</ref> He was hired to replace the outgoing [[Nobuhisa Tsukahara]], who was retiring due to health problems.<ref name="ap-djs"/> Soon after taking the post, he outlined a long term strategy for expansion by introducing a wider range of vehicles, and to undercut competitors by focusing on low cost manufacturing.<ref name="ap-djs"/><ref name="autonews">[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-18989155.html " Mitsubishi priority: more new product. (interview with Mitsubishi Motors Corp. President Takemune Kimura)(Talk from the Top)(Interview)"], James B Treece, ''Automotive News'', November 18, 1996</ref>
He and chairman [[Hirokazu Nakamura]] were forced to resign in December 1997, after four former company executives were jailed for making corporate payoffs to [[sōkaiya]] [[racketeer]]s.<ref name="japtimes">[http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/nn19971204a6.html "Mitsubishi Motors chief intent on turnaround"], Sayuri Daimon, ''[[The Japan Times]]'', December 4, 1997</ref><ref name="independent">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19971031/ai_n14140534 "Mitsubishi chiefs quit over 'gangster pay-off' scandal"], ''[[The Independent]]'' October 31, 1997</ref> Mitsubishi Motors admitted to paying [[Japanese yen|¥]]23.5&nbsp;million to the wife of a racketeer, ostensibly for the rental of a beach house, in a controversy which also engulfed [[Toshiba]] and [[Hitachi, Ltd.|Hitachi]].<ref name="independent"/><ref name="wards">[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3165/is_n12_v33/ai_20114855 "Lemonade time at Mitsubishi"], ''[[Ward's AutoWorld]]'', December 1997</ref><ref name="nyt">[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9403E2DA113EF937A15753C1A961958260 "3 Mitsubishi Executives Arrested in Payoffs"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 24, 1997</ref>
He was among those former executives named in 2005 in a ¥1.3&nbsp;billion lawsuit filed by Mitsubishi Motors in connection with the [[Mitsubishi Motors recall cover up]] scandal,<ref name="times">[http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/engineering/article440875.ece "Mitsubishi seeks £6.4m damages"], Christine Buckley, ''[[The Times]]'', March 31, 2005</ref> but died of [[bile duct]] [[cancer]] in 2006 before the case was resolved.<ref name="obit">[http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/summary_0198-290277_ITM "Ex-MMC Pres. Kimura, recall-related damages suit defendant, dies"], ''Knight-Ridder Tribune Business News'', February 14, 2006</ref>
